        "stores_heading": "Lucira's Experience Stores"
      }
    },
    "information_content_info_agKa4z": {
      "type": "information-content-info",
      "blocks": {
        "heading_rziKHm": {
          "type": "heading",
          "name": "Other Metrics & Interesting Comparisons",
          "settings": {
            "text": "Other Metrics & Interesting Comparisons",
            "heading_level": "h2",
            "heading_id": "other",
            "alignment": "left"
          }
        },
        "richtext_femnnD": {
          "type": "richtext",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<p>Let’s explore advanced tools and concepts to analyze gold pricing, trends, and predictions on a deeper level.</p>"
          }
        },
        "heading_CUMGGg": {
          "type": "heading",
          "name": "Gold To Silver Ratio",
          "settings": {
            "text": "Gold To Silver Ratio",
            "heading_level": "h3",
            "heading_id": "silver",
            "alignment": "left"
          }
        },
        "richtext_4cHGJz": {
          "type": "richtext",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<p>In this ratio we look at how many ounces of silver can buy you one ounce of gold. Gold to silver ratio helps investors realize whether gold is overpriced or undervalued in relation to silver. When the Gold to Silver ratio is high, gold is expensive and overpriced in comparison to silver but when the ratio is low, gold is undervalued or silver is expensive. This can help you decide which precious metal  to invest in at any given time.</p>"
          }
        },
        "heading_dVKrYR": {
          "type": "heading",
          "name": "Gold Price Over 10 Years",
          "settings": {
            "text": "Gold Price Over 10 Years",
            "heading_level": "h3",
            "heading_id": "tenyears",
            "alignment": "left"
          }
        },
        "richtext_NQzYn7": {
          "type": "richtext",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<p>For long term investors, calculating the ROI on Gold price over 10 years can be another great metric to compare with other investment options. To calculate the return on gold in the last 10 years, you can simply subtract the value of gold 10 years ago today from the current rate, and multiply it with the amount of gold (weight) you’d want to invest in to arrive at a solid figure. You can then compare it with other investment options to make a strategic decision based on current and past data and price trends.</p>"
          }
        }
      },
